<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Declines in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction spending
dropped by 1.8 percent in May, the worst showing in more than
three years, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that construction spending totaled a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 585 billion dollars, compared
with 595.7 billion in April.
</P>
<P>
The 1.8 percent decline, which followed 0.3 percent gains in
both April and March, was the worst since a 3 percent drop in
January 1994.
</P>
<P>
The drop in May was led by a 6 percent decrease in government
construction to an annual rate of 131.3 billion dollars. It was
also the worst decline since January 1994. Spending for highways
and streets, schools and public buildings all fell.
</P>
<P>
Non-residential commercial construction also fell by 0.6
percent to a rate of 160.4 billion dollars in May, led by declines
in spending for hospitals, private school and college buildings
and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residential spending edged down 0.2 percent to a
rate of 253.6 billion dollars. A 1.1 percent drop in single-family
spending offset gains in spending on remodeling and apartment
construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
