<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lingua Franca Proposed for ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today proposed that
the Malay and Indonesian languages be made the lingua franca for
ASEAN member countries, besides English.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made today by Malaysian Information Minister
Mohamed Rahmat at a meeting of the ASEAN Committee on Culture and
Information (COCI) in Langkawi, northern Malaysia, according to
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The time has come to consider another language, other than the
official language English, which could be used as the medium of
communication between the peoples of ASEAN, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the proposal was to foster greater rapport
among the peoples of the ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore, Brunei, Thailand, the Philippines
and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
