<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana to Sell 25.3 Tons of Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Botswana will sell 25.3 tons
of ivory from its 30-ton stockpile following the downlisting of
elephant population to Appendix II of the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species, Botswana Commerce and
Industry Minister George Kgoroba said today.
</P>
<P>
The planned sale represented the maximum allowed by CITES for an
experimental phase of the downlisting in the trade of ivory, Kgoroba
said.
</P>
<P>
The Botswana ivory is to be shipped to Japan for sale through that
country's Ivory Carvers' Association, he said.
</P>
<P>
The shipment of the ivory to Japan will only take place in about 18
months, once Botswana has put in place measures to safeguard the ivory
and control poaching.
</P>
<P>
Kgoroba warned that any increase in poaching and illegal trade in
ivory could end with Botswana's elephant population being placed
back on CITES' Appendix I.
</P>
<P>
Much of the ivory in Botswana's stockpile is of uncertain origin
since it was seized from international poachers at border posts.
</P>
<P>
Kgoroba stressed that Botswana would abide by the conditions laid
down by CITES for the ivory sale to enhance its bid to trade in all
elephant products.
</P>
<P>
Botswana reportedly has an elephant population of nearly
80,000, and the population is increasing by five percent a year.
enditem

