<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Security Cooperation Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai confirmed today the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
has resumed security cooperation with Israel following a series
of secret contacts.
</P>
<P>
Appearing before the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee, Mordechai said Palestinian and Israeli security
forces had resumed the cooperation which has been halted for more
than three months since Israel began building the controversial
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the security cooperation led to the tuning
down of Palestinian rioting in Hebron recently with fewer
protesters joining clashes with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Local media disclosed today that the security cooperation was
the result of a series of secret contacts, including the one
between Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and
PNA deputy Chairman Abu Mazen two weeks ago. PNA leader Yasser
Arafat held talks with Israeli Army security official Brigade
General Herzl Getz last Saturday in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Israel reportedly agreed to relocate a
controversial monument erected by Jewish settlers at the junction
of the Morag settlement in Gaza, in memory of a soldier killed in
last September's bloodshed. The monument triggered violent
Palestinian protests that spread later into Hebron.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai still complained that the security cooperation
was still not complete and hoped the two sides would continue
negotiations in order to achieve full resumption of the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the two sides are negotiating over the
opening of an airport and seaport in the Gaza Strip. He said
Israel must stand firm on strict security control at the Gaza
airport because Israel fears that the PNA could use the airport to
acquire weapons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources said that the resumption of security
cooperation was a positive step toward restarting the deadlocked
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. They noted that the Palestinian
side no longer conditioned the resumption of security cooperation
on Israel's halt to the Har Homa construction.
</P>
<P>
In another positive development, Israel Radio said that
Israeli police Inspector-General Assad Hafetz has been invited by
his Palestinian counterpart to visit Gaza late this month. The
visit is expected to focus on further security cooperation on
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of South Lebanon where Israel is bogged down in a
tough guerrilla war with Hezbollah forces, Mordechai reiterated
that he was opposed to the idea of unilateral withdrawal of
Israeli troops. But he confirmed the press reports about his
proposal put forward during a recent tour to Paris that France and
United States forces could replace Israeli troops in South
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said Israel has no intention of remaining in the
occupied South Lebanon, and its troops would be happy to leave if
the Lebanese army, supported by French or U.S. forces, could be
redeployed in the area.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition lawmakers doubted the feasibility of the
Mordechai proposal. Labor's lawmaker Shlomo Ben Ami said this was
a non-starter, because Syria opposes any presence of international
forces in Lebanon, and will not agree to let Israel off the hook
before reaching full Israeli-Syrian peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
