<HEADLINE> Seminar on Anti-TB Drugs Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A four-day seminar on production,
marketing, distribution and quality control of anti-tuberculosis
(TB) drugs in South Asia opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Attending the seminar are TB control managers, drug quality
controllers and doctors from Nepal, India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka,
all members of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), which also groups Bhutan, Bangladesh and the
Maldives.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the seminar organized by the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Tuberculosis Center, Nepali Health Secretary Sriram Poudel said
regular supply of good quality anti-TB drugs is very important for
the success of national TB control programs.
</P>
<P>
He said recommendations from the seminar will help the
government develop a suitable strategy for the management of
anti-TB drugs, which is the basic requirement for effective TB
control not only in this region but all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The world today has about 10 million TB patients, and one
million people die of TB every year in South Asia alone.
</P>
<P>
Director of the SAARC Tuberculosis Center Dr. Dirgha Singh Bam
said the primary strategy of TB control is based on the ability to
quickly identify and cure new TB patients in the community.
</P>
<P>
Regular drug supply needs concerted efforts to guarantee
procurement of anti-TB drugs of assured quality at affordable
prices and to make sure that drugs are distributed to patients on
time, said Dr. Bam, adding that short course chemotherapy is
proved to be a highly effective treatment for TB patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
