<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Set Up Strategic Commissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today said some strategic commissions will be set up within the next
few months to look into the elimination of monopolies and advise the
government on tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the Third Session of the Fourth Parliament,
Mugabe said an industry and trade commission should be fully
operational before the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
''The commission will spearhead the elimination of monopolistic
tendencies in the economy, leading to healthy competition,'' said
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Most monopolies in the provision of goods and services were held
by government-owned parastatals.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''a tariff commission will be established to advise on
appropriate tariff regimes in a systematic manner and the legislative
framework for the establishment of the commission will be put in
place during this session.''
</P>
<P>
The other commissions to be set up would be the education and
health review, said mugabe. enditem

