<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Engine Overhaul Venture Formed in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Pratt &AMP; Whitney (P&AMP;W) and SIA
(Singapore Airlines) Engineering Company (SIAEC) formed a joint
venture to overhaul and repair JT9D, PW4000 and CFM56 engines in
Singapore in a major effort to expand their respective service
businesses, the SIA announced here today.
</P>
<P>
It said that P&AMP;W, a United Technologies company, will own 51
percent of the venture, while SIAEC, a fully-owned subsidiary of
Singapore Airlines, owns the remaining 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
The initial work force and management for this venture will
come from SIAEC's current engine overhaul shop, with P&AMP;W providing
the general manager and specialist support.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture company will be P&AMP;W's exclusive Center of
Excellence facility in the Asia-Pacific and Indian subcontinent.
And the initial focus of the joint venture will be on P&AMP;W's PW4000
and JT9D series engines and the CFM56 engine built by CFMI, all of
which are currently used to power aircraft in Singapore Airlines
fleet.
</P>
<P>
The facility will expand into servicing other engine models in
the future, if this is considered to be financially viable, the
SIA said.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture company is expected to grow in tandem with
the rapid growth of the aviation industry in the Asia Pacific
region with an annual revenue of about 300 million US dollars by
the year 1999, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
