<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Renames Kowloon Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kowloon Customs House has been
renamed "Shenzhen Customs House", according to the General
Administration of Customs of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
"The renaming of the Kowloon Customs is an indication that
China has resumed the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong, and
that the Chinese government adheres to the solemn promise of 'one
country, two systems' and 'Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong',"
said a senior official from the Chinese Customs.
</P>
<P>
The Kowloon Customs House was opened in 1887, with the office
of the customs house based on the Hong Kong island while its
border posts located on Kowloon Boundary Street and a small island
near the Hong Kong island.
</P>
<P>
But after the new territories of Kowloon peninsula was forcibly
leased to Britain in 1898, the border post had to be moved to
Shenzhen. In 1949 after the founding of New China, the Chinese
Liberation Army took over the Anti-Smuggling Headquarters in
Shenzhen of the Kowloon Customs House and on the same date, the
office of the Kowloon Customs House declared to accept the
leadership of the Central Government.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government at the time declared that Hong Kong is
the Chinese territory and the Chinese government would not
recognize the three unequal treaties forced upon China by
colonialists. On December 14, 1950, the Central Government decided
to open a customs house (in Shenzhen), retaining the name "Kowloon
Customs House" and moving the office from Hong Kong to
Shenzhen. So the Kowloon Customs House is the only customs house
that did not use its place name.
</P>
<P>
A renaming ceremony will be held on July 2 in Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
