<HEADLINE> Nationwide Activities Mark Hong Kong's Return (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In east China's Shanghai city, citizens held a grand gathering
in the Exhibition center and a float parade outside the center
during day. The crowd shifted to the Oriental Pearl Tower at the
bank of the Huanghu river as over 5,000 actors and citizens staged
a musical show. The metropolitan skyline was lit up with fireworks
resembling bauhinia flowers, the insignia of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
A university freshmen Pu Siyi was among the 10,000-plus people
flocking to the Nanjing Road in downtown Shanghai to spend the
sleepless first night after Hong Kong's home-coming.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai is located at the head of a dragon--the Yangtze
River. Hong Kong is one of the four little dragons in Asia. We and
Hong Kongers are both descendents of the dragon. Therefore we are
closely linked strong ties," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Tianjin, the biggest port city of north China, all streets
and lanes have been decorated with red lanterns and colorful
flags, but the most popular decoration and symbol of national
pride is the five-star national flag.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has opened the gates of all its park free to the
public today. Most of them held outdoor performances to mark the
arrival of the long-awaited day.
</P>
<P>
A major ceremony was also held by Tianjin Municipal Government
this morning in the city's stadium. About 3,000 people from the
city's professional and amateur troupes gave performances at
gathering, presided over by city mayor Zhang Lichang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
