<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nationwide Activities Mark Hong Kong's Return (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Fuzhou, the hometown of a Qing Dynasty official who
destroyed over 20,000 baskets of British opium in 1839, people of
all ages and from different walks of life visited the memorial of
the official Lin Zexu, paying tribute to his status.
</P>
<P>
The memorial has been designated by the central government as
one of the national patriotism education centers.
</P>
<P>
Zhen Guofeng, a staff member of the provincial People's
Congress, said that the personal tragedy of Lin Zexu was a
reflection of the national tragedy at that time. "Now Lin can rest
in peace since we have resumed the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The smooth handover of Hong Kong today should be attributed to
the country's reform and opening up drive and the growth of
national strength," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Zhenzhou city in central China, 1,997 people carried a
1,997-meter-long dragon in a dance performance at the bank of the
Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River is believed to be the birthplace of the
Chinese nation, while dragon is a symbol of the national spirit.
</P>
<P>
Beside the dragon were 155 plates, each bearing the account of
a year of the 155 years since Britain seized Hong Kong from China
by force in 1842.
</P>
<P>
In Urumqi, the capital city of north China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, some 10,000 people from all walks of life
gathered at the central square this morning to watch the first
raising of the national flag after the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Among the crowd were 62 pairs of newlyweds who gathered for a
joint wedding ceremony. One couple said they timed their wedding
to coincide with the return of Hong Kong because it is "an
honorable and memorable event." 
</P>
</TEXT>
