<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Threatens Not to Attend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash threatened today not to participate in the upcoming
U.N.-led direct negotiations between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides if he is not informed of a document beforehand.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader made the remark before a meeting
of the self-styled parliament in the Turkish-occupied part of
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"If they (the U.N.) intend to give us a document of an unknown
content, I think I will not go to New York," Denktash was quoted
as saying by the Turkish Cypriot radio Bayrak. The document is
expected to be presented to both sides at the start of their talks.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot parliament convened today to discuss the
Cyprus question and the U.N.-sponsored face-to-face negotiations
between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash, which
are to be held near New York from July 9 to 13.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said he has asked U.N. resident representative in
Cyprus Gustave Feissel to tell him of the content of the document,
but received no reply so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, Denktash claimed that the idea of
presenting the two sides with a document came after a meeting
between Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides and U.N.
secretary-general's special representative for Cyprus Diego
Cordovez.
</P>
<P>
Denktash also claimed that the document will be put forward in
an expression of support to President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took control of the northern third of the island in the wake
of an pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side unilaterally declared a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in November 1993,
which was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash held two informal meetings in Nicosia in
October 1994 under the U.N. auspices, which ended in
deadlock. They have not met ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
