<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital City Celebrates Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Elderly Beijing resident Qin Shujun
woke up today to find herself two hours behind schedule for her
daily stroll in the park. Still, she got there before her fellow
walkers.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the Chinese capital overslept this morning.
</P>
<P>
Round-the-clock live broadcasts of the return of Hong Kong kept
most Beijing locals riveted to their TVs last night. Qin didn't
call it quits until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Beijingers' enthusiasm never seemed to wane on the night of
Hong Kong's homecoming. Qing and her friends hailed each other
with words spoken during the handover ceremony, or by counting
down from 10 to 0, just as millions of capital city residents had
done at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
The capital today remained drenched in a sea of lanterns,
decorations, flowers and banners commemorating the Hong Kong
return.
</P>
<P>
National flags were flying on every street and hutong, or
alley. Last week, Mi Huiming put a flag, which she bought together
with her neighbors, outside her house. "It is a typical way of
celebration for ordinary Chinese people," Mi said.
</P>
<P>
Buying miniature sets of the national flag and the
bauhania-patterned flag of the new Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region has been a year-long fad in the city. Local
flag peddlars feel blessed. One, stationed at Tian'anmen Square,
reportedly sold over 2,500 flags on a single day.
</P>
<P>
No. 49, Dongtangzi Hutong, is the spot where the Kowloon
Extension Agreement was signed in 1898, which further ceded the
Hong Kong New Territories to Britain. Today, a group of residents
there performed the "yangko" dance, a traditional rural folk
dance.
</P>
<P>
"Yangko dancing is the best way we can find to express our
joy," said one 65-year-old.
</P>
<P>
"What I feel most deeply is that weak countries will never
realize equal status with the world," said Zou Yuan, a retired
government official. "Only a powerful country and the return of
Hong Kong could wash away the humiliations experienced by the
Chinese."
</P>
<P>
It was just a few seconds after midnight last night when
Beijing Hospital for Gynecology and Obstetrics announced the birth
of the first baby born since the return of Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
