<HEADLINE> Gala at Opium-Burning Site To Welcome Hong Kong Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DONGGUAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong homecoming celebration
party at Dongguan today featured singing, dancing and fireworks
because of the history standing behind the city, and the
significance it represents in this historic day.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of Hong Kong's return, what first came into
the minds of the people in Dongguan is to send the good news to
their perished great and great-grandfathers, who have died in the
resistance battles against British colonialists over a century ago.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people gathered here, in a square called
"peace" in Humen of Dongguan city in southern China's Guangdong
province, to take part in the gala party to welcome Hong Kong back
with a variety of performances.
</P>
<P>
Standing behind the performing stage in the square were relief
sculptures, which showed the viewers what happened 158 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The national hero Lin Zexu led the move to burn more than 1.15
million kilograms of opium confiscated from British smugglers in
Humen then, the very beginning of a long-lasting resistance
against the international invaders.
</P>
<P>
But people at the party said they would rather look ahead into
the future. "We are fully convinced that Hong Kong, the orient
pearl which catches worldwide attention, will become all the more
brilliant after returning to the embrace of our motherland," said
Zhang Guoying, deputy secretary of the Provincial Committee of the
Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Sitting next-door to Hong Kong, the former opium-burning site
is booming with more than 10,000 joint ventures, with 90 percent
of the investment coming from Hong Kong investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
