<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Congratulates China on Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri today expressed his warm congratulations to China on
resuming the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong and his wish
for enhanced economic ties with this booming town.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister extended the good wishes a day after Hong
Kong, the once-lost Chinese territory returned to its motherland
following 156 years of British rule.
</P>
<P>
During an inspection trip to the Toshka Canal project which is
under construction in the Western Desert, Ganzouri told Xinhua
that he had sent congratulatory telegrams first to Chinese
Premier Li Peng and then to Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwua on the historic event.
</P>
<P>
"It is a really wonderful thing for China and different
countries all over the world, especially Egypt because our country
is one of the most friendly to China," said the Egyptian premier.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa had flown to Hong Kong to
attend the celebrations at midnight on June 30 marking the
inauguration of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to cooperation prospects between Egypt and
China, Ganzouri said that he is optimistic that bilateral ties and
trade and economic ties in particular, will be boosted in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt has invited some Hong Kong businessmen to come
here to explore joint projects.
</P>
<P>
"I think we are going to have these companies to deal with us
in the Mediterranean port city of Sharq el-Tafreaa and on the
Sinai peninsula. We expect some companies will come here very
soon," he added.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade exchange between Egypt and Hong Kong has
reached 380 million U.S. dollars within the past three years,
according to Egypt's Consul General to Hong Kong Ali Maher el-Dali.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from Hong Kong to Egypt has quadrupled
from 4,500 in 1993 to 18,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri visited China in late April in a bid to boost trade
between the two countries. Egypt and China are preparing to
establish a free trade zone in Suez city, about 150 kilometers
southeast of Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
