<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welfare Law Becomes Effective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The controversial law
overhauling the federal welfare system of the United States went
into effect today, with the states ready to take over assistance
to the poor.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law signed last year, able-bodied adults must get
a job within two years of receiving their first assistance check
or be dropped from the rolls. All recipients will be dropped from
the rolls after five years of assistance.
</P>
<P>
The law dismantles the existing federal welfare structure,
converting those programs into block grants for the states, which
will be able to set their own welfare rules and manage their own
programs. All the states have submitted their assistance plans to
the federal government -- except two that sought delays on
technicalities.
</P>
<P>
Welfare recipients who receive food stamps must find at least
part-time employment within three months of qualification for the
food-stamp program.
</P>
<P>
Congress is remedying one provision that would have denied
benefits to legal immigrants. Under the fine print in legislation
passed by the House of Representatives and Senate last week,
benefits are being restored to nearly 500,000 legal elderly and
disabled immigrants.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton signed the welfare bill last August
despite heavy fire from advocacy groups for the poor and religious
organizations that contended it was a brutal measure that would
pull the financial rug from under many poor people, especially
children.
</P>
<P>
He had vetoed two previous welfare reform proposals passed by
Congress. But, under pressure to remove a dangerous election-year
obstacle, he signed the third measure, which sought to end a
61-year-old New Deal guarantee of cash assistance for the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Gives Green Light to Merger of Boeing, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Trade
Commission (FTC) announced today it will not block the large
merger of Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas Corp., which would
create the world's largest aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
While confirming the widely expected decision, an FTC official
said the merger would not substantially decrease competition for
either military or civilian aircraft manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The FTC indicated that McDonnell Douglas ceased to be a
competitive factor in the market for commercial jets. Last year,
the company won only 4 percent of new airplane orders.
</P>
<P>
The proposed merger deal between the two aerospace giants is
considered as less of a merger and more of a buyout of McDonnell
Douglas by Boeing. Last December, Boeing announced to offer some
13.3 billion U.S. dollars in stock for McDonnell Douglas, based in
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
The deal would create a civilian- and military-aircraft
powerhouse with more than 200,000 employees and projected annual
revenues of 48 billion dollars. It would have 65 percent of the
world jetliner market, almost double the share of its only rival,
Europe's Airbus Industrie consortium.
</P>
<P>
European Union antitrust investigators continue to review the
merger to ensure it complies with the trade bloc's rules.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the European regulators and Boeing face a
Friday deadline for a vote by the antitrust advisory panel of the
European Union in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the deal also needs the shareholders approval from
both companies before the merger can take effect. Shareholder
meetings are scheduled for July 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Third Annual ESAF Loan for Togo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) today approved the third annual loan under the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) for Togo in an amount
equivalent to some 30 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The loan is provided in support of the Togolese government's
1997 economic program. The loan is available in two semiannual
installments, the first of which is available immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Togolese government's 1997 program is designed to correct
the weaknesses that occurred in 1996, particularly in the fiscal
consolidation efforts, and to accelerate the implementation of the
agreed structural reforms. For 1997, the country's real GDP is
expected to grow at a rate of 5.8 percent, the inflation rate is
to be reduced to 3.9 percent on average for the year, and the
current account deficit is to be narrowed to 6.6 percent of GDP,
from 8.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Togo joined the IMF in August 1962. Its quota is about 76
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals some 82 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tea Production Expected Lower Than Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- As global tea production is
expected to be lower and demand is likely to remain stable in
1997, consumers will face higher world tea prices, the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said today.
</P>
<P>
In Sri Lanka and in most tea producing countries of Africa,
extremely dry weather adversely affected crops, particularly in
Kenya where production in the first quarter was about 37 percent
lower than in the same period in 1996, according to a FAO report
available here today.
</P>
<P>
The report was prepared for the meeting of the
Intergovernmental Group on Tea in Bali, Indonesia, on July 2-4.
</P>
<P>
World tea production reached a record level of 2,691,000 tons
in 1996 and was 3 percent (about 75,000 tons) higher than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Harvests were larger in almost all major tea producing
countries in 1996, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
In India, production increased by 4 percent to set a new record
of 778,900 tons, In Africa, Uganda reported an increase of 26
percent, Malawi of 8 percent and Zimbabwe of 6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
