<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accepts NATO Proposals for Easing Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey decided to implement the
confidence building measures proposed by NATO Secretary General
Janvier Solana unilaterally to ease tensions in the Aegean, a
Turkish official statement said here today.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the Foreign Ministry said that Turkey
supports Solana's contacts with Turkey and Greece, adding that
it is ready to accept his proposals as a whole regarding
reciprocal implementation of effective confidence building
measures in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out: "Turkey unilaterally decided to implement the
proposals of the NATO secretary general from July 1 to August 15
in order to enable Greece to implement the proposals and to
consolidate the security atmosphere between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
If Greece responds to the good-will gesture of Turkey, then
the latter will accept the proposals of Solana who aims to extend
the moratorium till September 15 and if Greece fully implements
them, then Turkey will accept the extension of the moratorium for
another three months in 1998, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ankara decisions, Turkish aircrafts will be
disarmed when operating over the Aegean, aircrafts will use the
codes proposed by NATO, Turkey and Greece may be able to start
exchange of information on flights over the Aegean in case there
is a consensus of opinion to open communication circuits of
regional operation centers which are an important element of air
defense system by Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
A military statement issued today by the Turkish General
Staff said: "The Turkish navy and air force will carry out
routine training and reconnaissance activities in the Aegean
between July 1 and August 15, but there will be no manoeuvers
during the period."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been at odds with Greece over a number of
sensitive issues, including territorial disputes over islands in
the Aegean, mineral rights in the sea as well as the Cyprus
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
