<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Peace Talks to Resume Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOSHKA, EGYPT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said here today he hopes the Palestinians and Israelis
would succeed in agreeing on resuming talks for peace within the
coming few days.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters during a trip to the construction site of
the Toshka Canal, about 900 kilometers south of the capital,
Mubarak said the Palestinian and Israeli sides had been making
contacts during recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
The canal is designed to carry Nile water to irrigate part of
the Western Desert in an ambitious land reclamation project of the
Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
The president declined to reveal what was going on during those
secret contacts between ranking Israeli and Palestinian officials,
which also involved his political advisor Osama el-Baz.
</P>
<P>
Baz, who was accompanying the president on the inspection tour,
refused to elaborate on the current contacts, saying that too much
talk could aggravate the peace crisis at such a delicate moment.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that his scheduled weekend trip to Israel has
been postponed due to the lack of a breakthrough in the deadlocked
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has intensified its mediation efforts after U.S. envoy
Dennis Ross failed to bring the two sides back to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the recent U.S. Congressional resolution on
moving the American embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, the
president dismissed the move as "unwise" and likely to "add fuel
to the fire."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also ruled out the possibility that the U.S. is to
cease its aid to Egypt, as proposed by the U.S. Appropriations
Subcommittee on the ground that Egypt has stiffened its position
toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We have close friends in the U.S. Senate who are appreciative
of Egypt's position in this part of the world and on the peace
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was Egypt, and no other country, that opened the doors
before the peace process in the region," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In response to a decision by several Arab countries to boycott
the upcoming Doha Economic Summit which will include Israel,
Mubarak said each country should make its own decision in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
But the president refused to say if Egypt will go to the Qatari
capital in November for the Fourth Middle East and North African
Economic Summit.
</P>
<P>
"The whole thing will depend on the circumstances existing
before the convocation of the summit," he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel attended the third conference in Cairo last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
