<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Gives First Press Conference After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), said here
today that he is full of confidence in Hong Kong's prospects and
would make every effort to maintain the economic competitiveness
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center this afternoon, Tung, who was sworn in as the
HKSAR Chief Executive early Tuesday morning, told over 400 Chinese
and foreign journalists that the smooth handover of Hong Kong has
given the HKSAR a very good start.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong had been very fortunate to have a large
central delegation led by President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li
Peng here to attend the handover ceremony and the ceremony marking
the founding of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that President Jiang Zemin had reaffirmed again
that the principle of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong
people governing Hong Kong" with a high degree of autonomy would
remain unchanged for a long, long time, and that the Basic Law
will be observed by all departments of the central government and
all the provinces as well.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very good message for us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, he said, he had had opportunities to
meet many dignitaries from different countries, with whom he
established some friendships and shared the confidence in the
future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions on the Sino-British relationship, Tung said
it is very important for Britain and China to maintain good
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had had "very useful discussions" with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and Foreign Secretary Robin Cook while
they were in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese and British governments should put aside the past
and look forward to the future," he said, adding that "very good
signs" have appeared for future Sino-British relations.
</P>
<P>
Replying to another question, Tung said that the international
business community in Hong Kong will have as great a future as the
Chinese community, since Hong Kong will remain a cosmopolitan and
his government is determined to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the return of Hong Kong has provided a
successful example for solving international problems left over by
history, and will also help China's reunification.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of laws and amendments passed by the British Hong Kong
Legislative Council in the two and three weeks before the
handover, Tung said that these laws and amendments would have
long-term implications for the local community, but some of them
were passed "without proper study" and "certainly without proper
consultation".
</P>
<P>
"Each of these laws and amendments is being studied by the
administration, and we will do what is necessary to protect this
community," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Hong Kong and China's interior areas
share the same long-term interests, and Hong Kong people should
have a better understanding of their motherland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
