<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets up Distance Education Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Education Minister
Gabriel Machinga today inaugurated the country's national
association of distance and open learning (ZINADOL) which will
coordinate and oversee the activities of distant education and
correspondence institutions.
</P>
<P>
At a two-day meeting in Harare, Machinga said in spite of the
incredible development in education, millions of people of
different ages in both developing and industrialised countries
were still deprived of an opportunity to learn.
</P>
<P>
Since independence in 1980, he said, the Zimbabwean government
realised that universal education was not easy to achieve simply
through conventional approaches which entailed building more
schools, training more teachers, buying and providing more
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
ZINADOL is expected to monitor the operations of distance and
open learning institutions in Zimbabwe, as wells as to assist in
the training of personnel and to ensure the development of
quality instructional materials.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry had been working together with other
ministries, the university of Zimbabwe and commercial
correspondence colleges to provide alternative complementary
education to primary school leavers, as well as further education
opportunities to youths and adults.
</P>
<P>
ZINADOL would facilitate networking with other distance and
open learning institutions and similar bodies in the sub-region,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
