<HEADLINE> American Kids Better Educated...But Many Zonked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- More American children are
starting their education earlier and completing it with college,
but many of them are also likely to smoke or use drugs, a
government report released today says.
</P>
<P>
The report, compiling previously released statistics about
children, said more young people were attending early education
programs and graduating from college.
</P>
<P>
They were also getting immunized against childhood diseases and
were less likely to die during infancy and childhood.
</P>
<P>
However, the report found that more adolescents smoke and take
drugs than in the past.
</P>
<P>
It suggests the nation look for more accurate ways to measure
the number of homeless and poor children.
</P>
<P>
Ordered by President Bill Clinton, the report was compiled from
data contributed by federal agencies, including the departments of
Agriculture, Education, Health and Human Services, Housing and
Urban Development, Justice and Labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
