<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finance Minister Reports on 1996 State Revenues, Expenditures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government announced
that the increment of the state revenues last year was greater
than that of expenditures; and state financial deficit was lower
than expected.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli reported here today on central
government revenues and expenditures of the 1996 fiscal year to
the Standing Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress,
which is China's supreme legislature.
</P>
<P>
According to his report, the state revenues and expenditures
were "basically consistent" with the 1996 budget approved by the
top legislature.
</P>
<P>
State revenues increased in a considerably high rate, which was
2.7 percentage points higher than that of the expenditures.
</P>
<P>
However he also reported that the central government had a 1996
fiscal year deficit of 60.88 billion yuan, though it was 558
million yuan less than budgeted.
</P>
<P>
He said state revenues totaled 426.5 billion yuan in 1996, 8.37
billion yuan more than budgeted and 10.3 percent more than those
of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Among the total state revenues, the central government directly
collected 366 billion yuan, or about 86 percent. The rest were
turned over by various local governments.
</P>
<P>
He also said that state expenditures were 487.4 billion yuan
last year, 7.8 billion yuan more than budgeted and 7.6 percent
more than those in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Among the total state expenditures, the central government
itself spent 215 billion yuan, which is three percent less than
budgeted. Tax refunding and subsidies to local governments
totaled 272.2 billion yuan, 5.6 percent more than those targeted.
</P>
<P>
The financial minister said that the state budget for the 1996
fiscal year was basically well exercised. But he also pointed out
that problems existed.
</P>
<P>
Besides a rather-huge deficit, the problems he mentioned
included appropriation of tax revenues, unauthorized tax
exemptions, and escaping, avoidance and delay of the payment of
tax. 
</P>
