<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Pushes Construction of Regional Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Energy ministers from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) urged here today
the speeding up of construction of a trans-ASEAN gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day ASEAN Energy Ministers' Meeting, the
ministers agreed that it is without doubt that ASEAN countries
need to be linked by a natural gas network to ensure the long-term
energy security of the region.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN came up with the idea of building an 8,000-kilometer
undersea gas pipeline three years ago. The network, at an
estimated expense of 11 billion U.S. dollars, would connect
Brunei, Malaysia and Indonesia, the region's net gas exporters,
with gas importers including Thailand, Singapore and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The study for the feasibility of the plan undertaken by ASEAN
and a European consortium had been finished by July 1996 and a
final report was submitted to the energy ministers last year.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the ministers also agreed to include Cambodia,
Laos and Myanmar which would be admitted to ASEAN this month in
the planned gas pipeline network.
</P>
<P>
The network, planned to be completed within 10 years, will spur
the increased trade in natural gas within the region, the
ministers said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore,
Thailand, Vietnam and the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
