<HEADLINE> France to Reflect on Africa Policy in Open Way: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- France will reflect deeply on its
Africa policy, which is characterized by its military and
political alliance with countries that were formerly French
colonies, said French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine today.
</P>
<P>
"The government, as the president of the republic, thinks that
the era of unilateral intervention in Africa has passed," said
Vedrine at the French Senate.
</P>
<P>
He said that France should "reconsider in an open way, being
turned toward the future and the new elites," its relations with
France.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of France should be global and take into account,
with an open spirit, the countries and English-speaking Africa,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said that this did not mean that France would abandon
its African allies, but was a "redefinition of the whole of our
political, diplomatic and military actions on this continent."
</P>
<P>
On France's policy toward the on-going conflict in the Congo
Republic, Vedrine said that it was to "assist militarily all
foreigners" who wanted to quit the country, and diplomatically
provide mediation to the two warring factions while not letting
France get caught in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
France's Africa policy has been greatly shaken by the war in
former Zaire, and the newly erupting conflicts in the Congo
Republic and the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
France has deployed 1,850 soldiers in the Central African
Republic, 835 in Chad, 600 in Gabon, 520 in Cote d'Ivoire, 1,300
in Senegal, and 3,250 in Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
