<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denounces Turkish Parliament's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi National Assembly here
today denounced a recent Turkish Parliament decision to renew for
another six months the presence of the U.S. and British forces on
Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Ghanim Aziz Khaddori, acting chairman of the
Iraqi parliament, attacked the decision adopted last week as
"unjust, interfering in the Iraq's internal affairs, violating its
sovereignty and independence and contradicting the U.N. Charter
and international law."
</P>
<P>
According to the official Iraqi News Agency, Khaddori stressed
that the joint force was established under a bilateral agreement
between the U.S. and its other allies that has nothing to do with
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the "no-fly" zone in northern Iraq is illegal,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The acting chairman warned that the continuation of Ankara's
interference in Iraq's internal affairs does not serve Turkey's
national interests, and it will negatively affect its future
relations with Iraq and the Arab world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said that the
Turkish parliament's decision reflects Turkish politicians'
insistence on practicing the policy of bringing harm to Iraq and
its national security.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iraq holds Turkey fully responsible
for its "harmful" policy towards Iraq, which indicates Turkey's
"sorrowful non-respect" for the good neighborly relations,
international law and the U.N. charter.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of U.S. and British troops on Turkish territory
to patrol the "no-fly" zone in northern Iraq threatens the
security and sovereignty not only of Iraq but also of Turkey, the
spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq ended, the U.S., France,
Britain and Turkey built a joint air force and set up a "non-fly"
zone in northern Iraq to protect Iraqi Kurds from attacks by Iraqi
government troops.
</P>
<P>
France withdrew from the joint force at the end of last
year. The zone is patrolled at present by U.S. and British troops
which have their bases in Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
