<HEADLINE> Chinese People Respond Warmly to President's Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people from various walks
of life have responded warmly to President Jiang Zemin's speech
made at a public gathering in Beijing yesterday to celebrate the
return of Hong Kong -- an historic event which has aroused a
strong sense of patriotism throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Feng Jicai, a noted writer in Tianjin, said the return of Hong
Kong to the motherland begins a new chapter for China on the road
to prosperity and national strength.
</P>
<P>
He said that the return of Hong Kong also symbolizes China's
growing power and its regaining of self-respect after more than
half a century's struggle for reunification led by several
generations of the CPC leaders.
</P>
<P>
He said Jiang's speech was a call to all Chinese around the world
to work in one mind and one heart to invigorate the Chinese nation
and make always stand aloft among nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
79-year-old Wang Shen, who wrote the song "Sing the Praises of
Our Motherland" which was popular here 40-some years ago, said
that in the 19th century a poor China with a weak government
could not prevent British imperialists from occupying Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the leadership of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), the country has grown much stronger since the refrom
and opening up, and that being a powerful country was the
prerequisite for China's resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Abbot Bao Han in the Dabei Temple, a Buddhist temple in
Tianjin, said that to be a Buddhist one must love his country and
be faithful to his religious beliefs. He stressed that an
individual's patriotism should be his first priority.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong marks a milestone in China's
reunification process. It has inspired a love for the motherland
among religious people, who have pledged to contribute more to the
prosperity of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Sun Yan, a student from Nankai University, said the older
generations of revolutionaries are responsible for the founding of
New China and the construction of socialism, and the present-day
young intellectuals should strive to make China stronger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
