<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are business briefs from
the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's non-oil exports went up by 35.7 percent to
507.2 million U.S. dollars in the first two months of the current
Iranian calendar year starting from March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Today's Persian daily Iran reported that the exports showed
an increase of 29.5 percent in weight totalling 1.256 million
tonnes of non-oil goods.
</P>
<P>
Hand-woven carpets comprised 14.8 percent of the total
exports, pistachio 11.22 percent and steel and iron products
8.21 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Over this period, 2,961 tonnes of hand-woven carpets worth 43.9
million dollars were exported, up by 102.4 percent in weight and
56.9 percent in value compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural products worth 66.7 million dollars were exported
over the period, comprising 22.5 percent of the total exports.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- ECI Telecom, an Israeli high-tech company based in
Petah Tikva, north of Tel Aviv, announced that it has received a
54-million dollar deal to provide the Philippines Long Distance
Telephone Company (PLDT) with equipment for phase two of its "Zero
Backlog Program," The Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The equipment includes Access and SDH products. The
Philippines' plan is designed to provide 600,000 new subscribers
with telephone access by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The volume of tradings on the Egyptian stock markets
hit 12 billion Egyptian pounds (3.5 billion dollars) in the
first half of this year, almost tripling the volume of the same
period in 1996, the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The volume of shares traded in the first half of last year was
3.3 billion pounds (970.6 million dollars), according to Abdel
Hamid Ibrahim, chief of the Capital Market Authority that governs
operations of the stock exchanges in Cairo and Alexandria, a
northern coastal city.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference Tuesday that the newly-issued
securities including bonds and shares have risen to 9.1 billion
pounds (2.7 billion dollars) in the first six months of 1997 from
7.6 billion pounds (2.2 billion dollars) in the January-June
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of deals for the first half of this year, he said,
totaled 675,000, against 270,000 during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of companies undertaking these deals
surged to 289 from 262 last year.
</P>
<P>
To address a sharp price hike on the market at the start of the
year, the authority has put a five-percent limit on daily price
movement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
