<HEADLINE> Russian PM Vows to Guarantee Safety of Mir Crew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin pledged Tuesday to take every necessary measure to
ensure the personal safety of the three crew members in the Mir
space station and the normal operation of the station itself.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Interfax news agency, Chernomyrdin
said the health and safety of the two Russians and one American on
board the space station must be taken into consideration in the
first place when repairing the station, damaged in a docking
accident on June 25.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Mission Control said the situation on Mir is
"stable", and crew members "are working as planned".
</P>
<P>
The accident happened when a cargo craft, Progress, was docking
with Mir and mildly collided with the station. A scientific module
in Mir was holed during the collision and had to be closed.
</P>
<P>
Though part of the space station's oxygen was released and the
power system was damaged, the three astronauts survived the
accident unscathed.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reiterated that Russia will keep the promise
of building the Alpha international space station to replace the
aging Mir, the world's only space station, at the turn of the
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
