<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints Stepashin New Justice Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Wednesday appointed Sergei Stepashin Justice Minister of the
Russian Federation and dismissed the former minister, Valentin
Kovalyov.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted an official source as saying
the decision was made during today's meeting between Yeltsin and
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, 45, who has headed the Administrative Department of
the Russia government since November, 1995, was director of the
Federal Security Service in 1994-1995. He stepped down from the
latter post after the Chechen guerrilla's raid on the southern
Russian town of Budennovsk in mid-1995 which claimed more than 100
lives.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin on Monday appointed Georgy Kylikov acting Justice
Minister, sacking Kovalyov who was suspended following a sauna sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president also issued a decree today appointing
Mikhail Kislyuk, the governor of Kemerovo region, director of the
Russian Federal Service for the Regulation of Transport Natural
Monopolies.
</P>
<P>
Kislyuk takes over the post from Aman Tuleyev, whom Yeltsin on
Tuesday formally relieved of his duties as Minister for
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) Affairs, and appointed
him governor of the Kemerovo region, Siberia, the only governor
appointed in Russia by the presidential decree. 
</P>
