<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Takes Measures to Protect Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said here
today that the Philippine Central Bank has moved swiftly to
protect the peso following the announcement that Thailand has
devaluated its baht.
</P>
<P>
"The Central Bank has intervened effectively in this regard to
the floating this morning of the Thailand baht, which, of course,
created some negative spillover effects on the Philippines," Ramos
said.
</P>
<P>
The intervention, Ramos said, includes the raising of the
overnight interest rates to 24 percent and the buying of U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time that the country has raised its overnight
interest rates. Earlier this year, the country's overnight
interest rates stood at 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is just overnight that the peso has been effectively
protected from speculative attacks by some quarters as a result of
the spillover effects of the baht being attacked and depreciating,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the peso has remained steady at a rate of 26.35
pesos to one U.S. dollar at mid day today, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
"As we have been reporting, the peso during the past 12 months
has been fluctuating within a very, very narrow band range of
about 0.5 to one percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos recalled that during the Mexican financial crisis in
February 1995, the Philippine peso was also under attack, but
because of the proper intervention of the Central Bank, the entire
banking system and the government, the peso remained steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
