<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Becomes Sixth F-16 Fighter Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has produced its first
locally-made F-16 fighter, and become the sixth nation making the
F-16.
</P>
<P>
The other five producers are the United States, the
Netherlands, Denmark, Belgium and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Samsung Aerospace Industries Company spent 1.126 million
U.S. dollars in facility investments and employed a workforce of
4,000 experts over the past three years for the development of a
South Korean version of the fighter, the KF-16.
</P>
<P>
With the production of the fighter, South Korea's technological
levels in fighter production-management and test-evaluation have
reached 90 percent and 60 percent of those of advanced nations
respectively, Yonhap News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Defense Ministry plans to arm its air force with a
total of 120 F-16s by 1999: twelve directly imported in the first
phase, 36 assembled in South Korea in the second phase and 72
locally produced on permit from the licensee, Lockheed Martin
Corporation, the original F-16 maker in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The first KF-16 fighter, modelled after a U.S. Air Force
version, the F-16 C/D block 52, has an engine thrust of 29,000
pounds, 6,000 pounds more than existing F-16 fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
