<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Rebuffs President's Appointment Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino
today turned down a request by President Sali Berisha to appoint a
new interior minister after the serving incumbent fled the country.
</P>
<P>
Berisha last Tuesday demanded that one of his close aides, Azem
Hajdari, replace Belul Celo, who left Albania Wednesday, said a
statement issued by the prime minister's press office.
</P>
<P>
Fino, whose Socialist Party defeated the Democratic Party of
Berisha in last week's parliamentary election, described the
request as illegal.
</P>
<P>
He said that the president's appointment of a minister without
the prime minister's recommendation was not in line with the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Despite Celo's departure, he remained interior minister since
he did not offer a letter of resignation, Fino said. He added that
even if the post were vacant, Hajdari would not be a suitable
nomination.
</P>
<P>
The spat between the prime minister and the president comes
amid continuing tensions in the capital following the socialist
party's victory in the elections.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech on Monday, Berisha conceded the defeat of
his party and called for the restoration of order to the country
which was gripped by unrest and violence earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
But the president did not say whether he would step down. He
had hinted on several occasions after the turmoil began in March
that he would resign if his Democratic Party should lose to
leftists in the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
