<HEADLINE> France Supports Plavsic's Struggle With Other Bosnian Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed support for
Bosnian Serb president, Biljana Plavsic, in her confrontation with
hardline Serb leaders who are pressuring her to resign.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
Plasvic "has shown in the past her willingness to participate in
the peace efforts in Bosnia-Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
He also recalled France's demand that the Republika Srpska, the
Serb sub-state which takes up half of Bosnia, should "conform
itself to the peace agreements signed in Dayton and Paris."
</P>
<P>
"France would not tolerate the participation in the political
life of Bosnia by persons convicted by the International Criminal
Tribunal (in the Hague). The appearance of war criminals before
the Tribunal is for us a major concern," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serb ruling party, the Serb Democratic Party, has
asked the Bosnian Serb parliament to remove Plavsic from
presidency because of her recent dismissal of Interior Minister
Dragan Kijac.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic accused Kijac of refusing to cooperate with the
international police force, and having disbanded, without
consulting her, an intelligence and counter-espionage unit of an
anti-terrorist police brigade in Banja Luka, the northwest Bosnian
city controlled by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
She also charged Kijac, who is believed to be close to former
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, of organizing trafficking
and "turning the country into a private game preserve." 
</P>
