<HEADLINE> Children's Good Wishes Sailing to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Young Pioneers in Chongqing today
launched paper boats on a voyage from the Yangtze River to Hong
Kong, bringing with them the good wishes of children of this
largest municipality for children in Hong Kong that has just
returned to the motherland after more than a century and a half.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River was calm today. Under a bridge across the
Yangtze River in Chongqing, small paper boats were sailing towards
Tianmen one after another. Leading the fleet was a color paper boat,
trailing with colorful baloons. On the sail were inscribed with
"Hong Kong, Mother welcomes you".
</P>
<P>
"Every paper boat carries a good wish for Hong Kong," said
Huang Xiaoyan, a six grader whose vessel led the fleet on its long
journey. "I'm sending my greetings to the children in Hong Kong
with this paper boat and I wish Hong Kong a more brilliant future."
</P>
<P>
The most eye-catching creation is a remoted-controlled colorful
speed boat decorated with a national red flag and a regional flag
of Hong Kong. The owner was Zhao Xin, a senior middle school
student who won a number of national model vessel competitions.
</P>
<P>
"I am very pleased to participate in the event as part of my
activities to greet the return of Hong Kong," Zhao said. "I wish
Hong Kong will continue to develop and greet the future with a
brand new outlook."
</P>
<P>
The activities took place in the ports of Chongqing, Fuling and
Wanxian. Nearly 2,000 Young Pioneers participated in the
activities that launched 1,997 paper vessels, according to Hong
Tianyun, secretary of the Chongqing Municipal Committee of the
Communist Youth League. Endtiem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
