<HEADLINE> Nepal to Pursue Policy of Peaceful Coexistence: King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra said here
today that the Nepali government will continue pursuing a foreign
policy based on the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence and
promote sub-regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will make efforts to consolidate economic diplomacy in
conducting international relations and thus further its economic
interests, the king said when addressing a joint session of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said the country will undertake steps to help the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) take measures
to handle core economic issues for the common benefit of its
members and promote the concept of sub-regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC groups Nepal, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan,
Sri Lanka and the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
Birendra stressed that his government will look into every
alternative to resolve the problem of Bhutanese refugees.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese of Nepali origin fled to Nepal via
India in 1989 and they now live in eight camps in eastern Nepal,
causing many social and security problems.
</P>
<P>
The king said the visits of the Nepali prime minister to
Britain and Pakistan, those of the presidents of China and Germany
to Nepal last year, and the recent trip of the Indian prime
minister to Nepal have resulted in the strengthening of
traditional, close and friendly bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said his government believes that cooperation with Nepal
from the friendly donor countries will continue.
</P>
<P>
The 12th session of the Nepali Parliament began on June 26,
with the passage of the budget for the coming 1997-98 fiscal year
top on its agenda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
