<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Tanker Aground in Tokyo Bay Leaks Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A Panama-registered oil tanker loaded
with 250,000 tons of crude oil ran aground near the port of
Yokohama this morning, spilling a large amount of oil into Tokyo
Bay.
</P>
<P>
The spilled oil from the 147,012-ton Diamond Grace caused a
slick five kilometers long and three kilometers wide, sources from
the Maritime Safety Agency (MSA) said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Nippon Yusen K.K., Japan's top shipping company
which operates the tanker, said that by 12:55 p.m.(local time),
the ship had leaked about 11,000 kiloliters of oil.
</P>
<P>
The oil leak was stopped at 1:00 p.m., the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
After the accident occurred, the MSA immediately mobilized 10
vessels, including patrol ships, from its Yokohama regional branch
to fight the spill.
</P>
<P>
The MSA vessels have set up oil fences and are conducting
cleanup operations, the MSA officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Maritime Self-Defense Force (MSDF) also dispatched
three tugboats and other vessels to help spread oil fences in the
bay.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto met with representatives from
government agencies to discuss the oil spill and ways to minimize
its damage. They decided to set up a central emergency management
task force.
</P>
<P>
The 322 meters long and 58 meters wide tanker, built in 1994,
was carrying crude oil from the United Arab Emirates to a refinery
owned by the Mitsubishi Oil Co. Ltd., in Kawasaki near Yokohama.
</P>
<P>
It is the second oil spill in Japan's sea area this year. In
January, a Russian tanker split in two and sank in the Sea of
Japan off the western coast, dumping an estimated 5,000 kiloliters
of fuel oil and fouling hundreds of kilometers of shoreline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
