<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gemstone-Trading Liberalized in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
liberalized trading in gemstones by introducing new licenses to
enable Zambians and foreign investors participate fully in the
mining of the precious stone in the country.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Deputy Minister of Mines Kaunda
Lembalemba at a press briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
Lembalemba said that the new move has been tailored to benefit
and enable indigenous Zambians participate in exploiting and
enjoying the natural wealth endowed to them as it is dangerous to
only let foreign nationals exploit the wealth of the nation at
the expense of the local people.
</P>
<P>
Even villagers will be allowed to mine sections of their areas
endowed with gemstones, he said.
</P>
<P>
The time has gone when it was a big crime to trade in
gemstones since now any Zambian who wishes to trade in this
mineral needs only to obtain a gemstone sales certificate by
paying a total of 198,000 kwacha (150 US Dollars) in registration
fees, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Gemstones is one of the non-traditional products which is
boosted by the Zambian government for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
