<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kowloon Customs Is Renamed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- An official ceremony was held
today in the southern city of Shenzhen to rename the customs there
"Shenzhen Customs". The point was previously known as "Kowloon
Customs."
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin did the honor of providing characters for
use on name-board of the customs house. His calligraphy
reads: "Shenzhen Customs, People's Republic of China".
</P>
<P>
The name change emphasizes China's resumption of exercise of
its sovereignty over Hong Kong, while the maintenance of a customs
post at the boundary of the Special Administrative Region with
Shenzhen provides practical evidence of central government
adhering to its principle of "One country, Two systems."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Qian Guanlin, Director General of the
General Administration of Customs (GAC) of the People's Republic
of China, reiterated that Hong Kong Customs will retain its
independence in administration and the GAC will not interere with
such activities.
</P>
<P>
"Trade between Hong Kong and the inland areas will be regarded
as external trade between two different tariff areas under one
sovereignty state," Qian pointed out, adding that Hong Kong
investors in inland areas will continue to enjoy whatever
preferential treatment is granted to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Qian also stressed that Hong Kong is not subject to the Customs
Law of the People's Republic of China nor the regulations which
are applied by inland customs.
</P>
<P>
"On that basis, customs authorities of inland areas can develop
a good relationship with their Hong Kong counterpart, forging
closer links and having frequent exchanges of information "
explained Qian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0110 </DOCNO>
