<HEADLINE> Action Committees to Be Formed in Malaysia on Dengue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- All states in Malaysia were
today directed to set up action committees to check the spread of
dengue as the number of cases nationwide for the first half of
this year alone rose by 127 percent over the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
The decision to establish the committees was made at today's
cabinet meeting here, Housing and Local Government Minister Ting
Chew Peh said.
</P>
<P>
The committees are to submit weekly situation reports to his
ministry which is coordinating anti-dengue preventive measures, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters after the meeting that the cabinet
also decided that a one-month-long nationwide anti-dengue campaign
will be extended to last for three months.
</P>
<P>
He said he would also discuss with Education Minister Najib Tun
Razak a separate anti-dengue drive involving schools.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, 8,598 dengue cases have been
reported all over Malaysia so far this year, compared with 3,790
cases last year, an average increase of 127 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Federal Territory alone recorded a 130-percent
rise in the number of cases from 1,376 to 3,167 during the same
period, Ting said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
