<HEADLINE> Inter-Party Talks Put on Hold in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish Institute of Democracy
and Electoral Assistance (IDEA) has abandoned the inter-party
talks initiative because of what Times of Zambia today reported
as the disorganization displayed among opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
IDEA representatives Berhetesfu Constantinos and Nobby Ngobane
left here on Tuesday abruptly after a stormy meeting held here on
Monday, during which the opposition parties allegedly refused to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Michael Sata, National Secretary of
the ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD), as saying
that "they have gone back to Sweden but have left a warning that
the inter-party talks will not take place unless the opposition
reform and these parties will have to take the initiative to call
IDEA back."
</P>
<P>
The opposition Liberal Progressive Front (LPF) President Roger
Chongwe was quoted as attributing the departure to the failure by
political parties to agree on an agenda.
</P>
<P>
He insisted the National Patriotic Coalition (NPC) grouping 12
opposition parties has merely offered proposals and not
conditions for the proposed talks but the government has not
given its counter proposals to form the basis of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Chongwe said IDEA has indicated their disappointment, saying
they will only resume the initiative after the situation has
changed. 
</P>
