<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Ready to Strike in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Soldiers of the west African
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) massed in Sierra Leone are capable of
flushing out the coupists in that country, the force commander
has said.
</P>
<P>
The troops are only awaiting the go-ahead to strike, said
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu on Tuesday, who
arrived from Liberia where the multi-national force has been
operating for about seven years.
</P>
<P>
"We have the capability of flushing out those people if and
when we are directed to do so," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, the ECOMOG is waiting for the time of two
weeks given the ministerial committee by the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) to dialogue with the coupists,
after which other steps including an embargo and the use of force
will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Malu said, "we are not in Sierra Leone doing the type of job
we are doing in Liberia. We have not occupied the country for
security. we were there before the coup."
</P>
<P>
"What we did was to reinforce the troops in that place to
protect ourselves. As a matter of fact, we have not gotten any
operational order to go in to reverse the coup," he said.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS foreign ministers in a communique on June 26 resolved
that within two weeks, a committee comprising Nigeria, Ghana,
Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire should consult with the coupists in
Sierra Leone after which an embargo and force to unseat the
coupists will be used.
</P>
<P>
The coupists led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma have to either
resign and install elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah till July
10 or will face the wrath of ECOMOG troops currently occupying
part of capital Freetown, including the international airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
