<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia's Taylor Escapes Assassination Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Former Liberian warlord and one of
the country's presidential candidates, Charles Taylor, has
escaped an assassination bid in Monrovia, the capital, barely 17
days to the general elections.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG on Tuesday said three persons, including Managing
Director of the Liberian Forestry Development Authority, Madison
Wion, had been arrested in connection with the incident.
</P>
<P>
Wion had been found to be involved in the assassination
attempt and "he has confessed both in writing and on tape about
his full involvement in the plot to kill Taylor," said the
statement issued by Biola Lawal, press secretary to the ECOMOG
force commander.
</P>
<P>
"We are now putting together all the necessary document to
transfer the case to the Justice Ministry for further action," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The clarification, the statement said, became necessary to put
to rest the anxiety among Council of State members, the
Transitional Legislative Assembly and members of the public, who
over the past few days have expressed concern over the arrest of
the suspects.
</P>
<P>
The statement reiterated that the ECOMOG was not in Liberia to
intimidate anybody, but to perform its security duties as well as
prevent criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
"ECOMOG cannot fold its arms where individuals are planning to
assassinate political figures like Taylor, especially because of
the security implications," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force has repeatedly promised to provide
security to the Liberian populace, and politicians campaigning in
the hinterland in particular.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident, about 15 other Liberians have been
arrested by ECOMOG for electoral malpractices since registration
of voters started in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
