<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Prevent Disease Outbreak in War-Torn Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine health workers are now
taking all possible measures to prevent an outbreak of any disease
in the war-torn towns in Mindanao, the southern Philippines,
Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica said today.
</P>
<P>
Reodica said in a statement that medical teams on 24-hour
service are conducting disease surveillance and case treatment in
evacuation centers housing those who were displaced by recent
fighting between soldiers and Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
Reodica said cases of diarrhea, sore eyes and rabies are on the
rise in some evacuation centers, adding that her department will
send more doctors, nurses and sanitary engineers to these centers.
</P>
<P>
Reodica's announcement came a day after President Fidel Ramos
declared eight towns in the provinces of North Cotabato and
Maguindanao as calamity areas.
</P>
<P>
She said the number of the displaced who temporarily camped in
evacuation centers has soared to 65,500 after fierce clashes
between government troops and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Reodica said she will personally assess and oversee the
situation in at least 81 evacuation centers in North Cotabato,
which house about 39,000 people, mostly children.
</P>
<P>
Health officials are also conducting massive vaccination of
children against measles and other diseases, chlorination of
drinking water and intense health education and information.
</P>
<P>
So far, Reodica said, there is no reported outbreak of any
disease despite cases of illness being reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
