<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday published a report on
information trade, in which he adopted an extremely liberal
attitude toward government regulation of free flow of information
on the Internet -- no censorship of the contents and no regulation
of exchange of information worldwide. This will have a strong
impact not only on the United States, but also on the whole world.
</P>
<P>
-- Accused since July 1996 of "genocide" and crimes against
humanity, former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic has been
living safely in a house outside Pale, 15 kilometers from
Sarajevo, under heavy protection of Serb security force, from
which he is still controlling the Serb territory to the smallest
details through telephone conversations with his followers,
according to an officer of the NATO peace consolidation force SFOR
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Tuesday called on the
Socialist Party deputies not to take "untimely" positions by
blaming the government for the closure of Renault Vilvoorde auto
plant in Belgium, because that would encourage "certain parties"
in the majority -- by which he apparently referred to the
Communist Party, to raise their tone when criticizing the
government.
</P>
<P>
-- The number of automobiles sold in France dropped by 30.7
percent in June compared to that in May, amid a serious crisis of
the French auto market, where the registrations of new cars
decreased by 23.7 percent in the first half of 1997, compared to
the second half of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
