<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A combination of heavy buying,
positive economic news and the potential of a large cash injection
from offshore catapulted the Australian sharemarket to another
record closing high today.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade the benchmark all ordinaries index was
24.7 points higher at 2,745.9, eclipsing the previous record of
2,725.9 points set on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reynold &AMP; Co senior broker Peter Struk said the market was
perplexed by today's strong performance.
</P>
<P>
"No one expected it to be up by 25 points ... there's some
speculation around that when the market reopens in Hong Kong there
will be some overseas buying interest, notably London and
Australia," Struk said.
</P>
<P>
Traders also said the firmer close on Wall Street had set the
tone for today's solid market performance.
</P>
<P>
A broker said the mid-morning announcement by ratings agency
Mood'y Investor Services on the positive outlook for Australia's
credit rating had helped sentiment, but had not substantially
moved the market.
</P>
<P>
Retail stocks benefited from data from the Australian Bureau of
Statistics, which showed a 2.9 percent lift in retail trade in
May.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 38.8 points higher at
4,329.8 while the all resources gained 13.8 points to 1,523.1.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, National Australia Bank was up 37.1
cents at 19.39 Australian dollars, Commonwealth was up 17 at 16.01
Australian dollars, Westpac gained six to 7.97 Australian dollars
and ANZ was five firmer at 9.91 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traders said investors chasing yields and betting on a cut in
official interest rates were buying into the major banks.
</P>
<P>
On the resources front, market bellwether BHP gained 31 cents
to 19.83 Australian dollars and diversified miner Rio Tinto piled
on 50 cents to 22.97 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 0.1 point higher at 1,465.6 while in
Sydney gold bullion closed a 332.10 US dollars per fine ounce --
down from 333.75 US dollars Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 363.08 million shares traded with a value
of 930.12 million Australian dollars (697.59 million US dollars),
with rises of 703 outnumbering falls of 446.  
</P>
</TEXT>
