<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Standing Committee Reviews Auditing Report For Fiscal Year 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The 26th session of China's Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee here today
reviewed a report on last year's budget by Guo Zhenqian,
Auditor-General of the State Auditing Administration.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the NPC Standing Committee Qiao Shi attended the
session, which was presided over by Wang Guangying, Vice-Chairman
of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
in his report, Guo said that the country's financial condition
improved with the growth rate of revenues exceeding that of the
GDP for the first time in 1996. Generally speaking, he added,
implementation of the central budget in 1996 was good, and in
addition to revenue increases, expenditures were effectively
controlled and better used.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal year 1996 the central government's total revenues
were 2 percent more than expected, while expenditures were 1.6
percent more than expected, and the deficit 558 million yuan (some
69 million US dollars) less than expected.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, there were still problems in the
implementation of the central budget last year, including a lack
of strictness and standards, ineffective revenue management, and
illegal tax reductions and remittances.
</P>
<P>
He said that new methods, including strengthening
tax-collecting, standardizing special financial allocations from
the central bank to various local authorities, improving
management of the central government's special investment plans
for infrastructure, and improving the approval system for budgets
should be used to deal with these problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
