<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moody's Assessment Boosts Australian Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
firmer against the U.S. currency, gaining strength from the
release of an upbeat Moody's Investors Service report, but it was
still haunted by the specter of potential interest rate movements.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished in Sydney at 75.48 U.S. cents, after
trading in a range of 75.06 to 75.53 U.S. cents, and up from 75.21
U.S. cents late in local dealings yesterday.
</P>
<P>
One dealer said the catalyst for the day's strength was a
Moody's report which said the outlook for Australia's Aa2 rating
was improving.
</P>
<P>
The dealer said the local unit was now "basically on hold"
while it awaited the outcome, expected tonight, of the U.S.
Federal Reserve's two-day meeting on monetary policy and potential
movements in interest rates by its domestic equivalent, the
Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA).
</P>
<P>
The two countries' equivalent official rates are level at 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The markets do not expect the Federal Reserve to increase
rates. Yesterday, the RBA held its monthly meeting, but was silent
this morning about monetary policy. The RBA eased rates four times
in the past 12 months with the last easing on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Citibank economists Stephen Koukoulas and Annette Beacher said
the Australian dollar remained vulnerable to an easing, but was
positively influenced by the favorable outlook from Moody's.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended in Sydney at 86.47 Japanese yen, up
from 86.7, and at 1.317 Deutsche marks from 1.3141.  
</P>
</TEXT>
