<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Not to Hand back Nationalized Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government has
no plans to return nationalized schools to their owners, Deputy
Chief Minister and Minister for Education, Omar Ramadhani Mapuri,
has said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today from Zanzibar, while
winding up the debate on the Education Ministry's estimates for
1997/98 in the House of Representatives in the town of Zanzibar,
Mapuri said on Monday the schools were nationalized to provide
free education for children in the Isles after the January
Revolution in 1964.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the former owners could come back and
open new private schools in the Isles.
</P>
<P>
The deputy chief minister said the current Zanzibar laws do
not allow nationalization and that people should feel free to
open private schools to help educate the islanders and increase
admission of pupils.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mapuri said public schools have been unable to
satisfy the demand due to shortage of classrooms.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there has been a shortage of teachers
especially those handling science subjects. Classrooms are
congested and teachers are compelled to handle the overcrowded
classes, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, some other developing countries have been
also experiencing a similar problem due to the existence of
universal primary education aimed at fighting illiteracy in
respective nations.
</P>
<P>
On combating shortage of science teachers, Mapuri revealed
that talks are underway to bring in qualified teachers from
Nigeria to teach science subjects and geography subjects which
also lacked competent teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
