<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 08:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tradings Triple on Egyptian Stock Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The volume of tradings on the
Egyptian stock markets hit 12 billion Egyptian pounds (3.5 billion
U.S. dollars) in the first half of this year, almost tripling the
volume of the same period in 1996, the Egyptian Gazette reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The volume of shares traded in the first half of last year was
3.3 billion pounds (970.6 million dollars), according to Abdel
Hamid Ibrahim, chief of the Capital Market Authority that governs
operations of the stock exchanges in Cairo and Alexandria, a
northern coastal city.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference Tuesday that the newly-issued
securities including bonds and shares have risen to 9.1 billion
pounds (2.7 billion dollars) in the first six months of 1997 from
7.6 billion pounds (2.2 billion dollars) in the January-June
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of deals for the first half of this year, he said,
totaled 675,000, against 270,000 during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of companies undertaking these deals
surged to 289 from 262 last year.
</P>
<P>
To address a sharp price hike on the market at the start of the
year, the authority has put a 5 percent limit on daily price
movement.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, the market has been falling in what brokers
see as a "correction." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
