<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks in China Give Good Report on Yuan Business (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded banks in Shanghai
say that their months-old business in Chinese currency is going
well, hoping that China's central bank can raise the ceiling of
their funds in Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the central bank, has since last
December approved nine overseas-funded banks in Shanghai to deal
in yuan-based business on a trial basis in the city's Pudong New
Area, an emerging financial and trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The nine banks are the Citibank, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi
Ltd., the Industrial Bank of Japan, the Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corporation, the Daiichi Kangyo Bank, the Sanwa Bank, the
Standard Chartered Bank, the Banque Indosuez, and the
International Bank of Paris and Shanghai, a joint-venture between
France's Banque Nationale de Paris and the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Most of the banks have moved their Shanghai branches to Pudong
to qualify for dealing in yuan business. Since March 27, six of
them have offered yuan-based services.
</P>
<P>
Loans account for a major part of the banks' yuan business,
which also includes accepting deposits, providing guarantees, and
trading in treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
An official with PBC Shanghai says that the trial yuan business
of the overseas-funded banks has been going well and that no major
problems have been reported. To date nearly 140 overseas-funded
enterprises have opened yuan accounts at the Shanghai branch of
Japan's Sanwa Bank alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks in China Give Good Report on Yuan Business (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In interviews with Xinhua, the banks have expressed a common
wish to increase the amount of yuan funds at their disposal in
order to expand business.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Industrial Bank of Japan, Kiyoshige
Akamatsu, said that in less than three months Japanese-funded
enterprises have applied for about 300 million yuan in loans, as
opposed to the ceiling of 30 million in its disposable yuan funds
permitted by the PBC.
</P>
<P>
He explained that after a certain amount of funds are deducted
for other purposes, only 50-70 percent of the funds can be used
for loans. He added that overseas banks also have difficulty in
attracting yuan funds, because their sources of Chinese currency
deposits are limited to overseas-funded enterprises registered in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Overseas bank executives also note that their business in the
interbank money market is restricted by a maximum of 30 million
yuan allowed for by the PBC.
</P>
<P>
Akamatsu said that he is confident about the bank's prospects
in yuan business and that he expects yuan-based services to make
up about 10 percent of his bank's portfolio, as opposed to the 1
to 2 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
The overseas banks agree that at the current stage of
development, cooperation with Chinese banks far outweighs
competition in the yuan business, and that they hope for more
cooperation with Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Shanghai's Bank of Communications and Japan's Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd jointly offered 45 million yuan in loans to a
company here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
