<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Banks Urged to Be More Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- It is high time for African banks
to restructure their operations and be privatized in a bid to
compete more effectively in the global economy, Kenya Finance
Minister Musalia Mudavadi has urged.
</P>
<P>
The huge challenges facing African bankers currently are how
to keep pace with the changing world, he was quoted by today's
Kenyan Times newspaper as speaking at the first Commonwealth
Africa Banking seminar at Mombasa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of the banks should entail moving away from
the use of controls, including credit directives and
administrative interventions, so as to allow the banks a greater
role in the mobilization of savings, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that the economic reforms launched by the
Kenyan government four years ago have started yielding fruits
which are reflected in the reduction of inflation rate and the
stabilization of the Kenya Shilling.
</P>
<P>
Due to the economic reforms, the exchange rate in the eastern
African country is now market-driven apart from the tariffs being
restructured, he added.
</P>
<P>
"More important was the fact that the measures which made the
(Kenyan) economy more open, competitive and efficient have
stimulated progress in all spheres of economic activity," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
