<HEADLINE> Little of Lusaka's Refuse Collected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Only about 14 percent of the total
waste in Lusaka is collected, according to a local paper "The
Post" today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a joint report by the Environmental
Council of Zambia (ECZ) and Lusaka City Council (LCC) as saying
that out of 243,000 tons of domestic, commercial and
institutional waste generated per year in the capital city, only
30,000 tons are collected and disposed of.
</P>
<P>
ECZ Senior Inspector Peter Zulu said here on Tuesday that the
refuse uncollected causes numerous problems for the city.
</P>
<P>
"Lusaka is now known as the 'garbage city' and this
uncollected refuse is responsible to a large extent for waste
pollution, leading to outbreak of diseases like cholera and
dysentery in compounds," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The ECZ/LCC report cited lack of refuse collecting vehicles,
inadequate manpower and little training for the refuse collection
managers as some of the reasons for the city's inability to
collect garbage.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Lusaka has 19 vehicles for the
exercise with only eight functioning while the total work force
is 270, making it impossible to effectively cover the city.
</P>
<P>
Another serious problem is the deficiency in solid waste
storage in places like markets, residential areas, bus stops,
medical institutions, commercial and industrial areas, causing
refuse to be littered in all places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
