<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Population Figure Corrected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has a population
of 37.9 million, which is lower than the 1991 official count,
according to preliminary estimates taken from last year's census.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the Central Statistical Service (CSS) on
Tuesday, the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The CSS said it expected the total population to be more than
42 million people, based on the census in 1991, when South
Africa's total population was estimated to be 38 million.
</P>
<P>
The census' 96 preliminary figures, which focus mainly on the
size of the population, were released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
But the CSS said statistical information on population groups,
language, education and income among others still had to be
processed.
</P>
<P>
It said a special post-enumeration survey indicated an
undercount of 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This means that about seven people in every 100 across the
country were not counted. We accordingly adjusted the preliminary
estimates upwards," the CSS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
