<HEADLINE> Law on Sub-Standard Imports Hailed in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice President George
Saitoti has hailed a new legislation to curb dumping of shoddy
goods as announced in this year's budget, saying it will now give
local manufacturers an edge over imported goods.
</P>
<P>
The new anti-dumping law will check the importation of goods
and ensure sub-standard goods are not allowed into the country,
while the local firms will get the chance to compete fairly, he
was quoted by today's "Kenyan Time" newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of Kenya's economy has allowed the
unchecked imports of sub-standard commodities in the country,
forcing many local industries to close since they cannot compete,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many Kenyans have been forced into unemployment
following the closure of the firms, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also commended the new measures that have been put in place
to check the illegal diversion of foodstuffs destined for other
parts of the world into the eastern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
