<HEADLINE> Water and Sanitation Project to Start in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A water and sanitation project is
to start soon to increase access to safe water from 25 to 110
supply points for about 30,000 people in remote and drought areas
of Zambia's Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
An agreement of 542 million Kwacha (over 410,000 U.S.
Dollars) has been signed to this effect by the World Vision
(Zambia) and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The local press today quoted World Vision National Director
Bwalya Melu as saying, "under the agreement, a drilling
contractor will sink 55 new bore-holes and another 30 in existing
dry dug wells to help the local communities manage their own
water points."
</P>
<P>
The project also seeks to create awareness in the community on
the hygienic methods of human waste and garbage disposal and will
enable people to dig 1,000 garbage pits for demonstration and
construct 1,000 new pit latrines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
