<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 07:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reinforces Forces in Hebron to Prevent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- More Israeli troops have been
deployed in the flashpoint city of Hebron in brace for possible
escalation of Palestinian rioting, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reinforcements were sent to Hebron following Monday's
violent clashes in which two Israeli soldiers were wounded by
pipe bombs thrown by Palestinian rioters.
</P>
<P>
One of the wounded soldiers remained in serious condition in
Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital, while the other suffered only
light injuries. About 20 Palestinian protesters were wounded,
one of them seriously, by rubber bullets fired by Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The commander of Israeli forces in Hebron, Colonel Gadi,
reviewed the security situation overnight to prepare for the
escalation of violence. He accused the Palestinian police of not
attempting to stop the rioting, adding that his forces would
react with an "iron fist" to new violence.
</P>
<P>
Army Radio reported that Hebron troops had been ordered to
use more force to quell riots, though the Army's Central Command
denied any new orders had been given.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of violence was triggered by a provocative
leaflet which depicted the Islamic prophet Mohammed as a pig
writing the holy Koran. The leaflets were pasted on Palestinian
storefronts in Hebron over the weekend by a Jewish woman from
Jerusalem, who is now under police custody.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and President
Ezer Weizman have apologized for the provocative leaflet, which
has also sparked anger among Israeli Arab community.
</P>
<P>
Arab lawmakers and community leaders are to hold a meeting
Thursday to discuss their response to the leaflet. An Arab
committee has called on the government to remove all Jewish
settlers from the West Bank and Gaza Strip, especially those in
the center of Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
