<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Step up Coop With N. African States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki today is to start his visits to Tunisia,
Algeria and Mali to try to enhance political and economic ties
with the northern African countries.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry of South Africa said in a statement that
Mbeki would hold talks with key government officials and show
"South Africa's support for Algerian and Malian democracy".
</P>
<P>
Algeria recently conducted its first successful multi-party
elections, with a three-party coalition government formed on June
26.
</P>
<P>
Five years after their achievement of political freedom, the
people of Mali are about to go to the polls again.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, accompanied by Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad, also
expressed hope that South Africa could help to develop the
"untapped mining, agricultural and other resources" in the north
African states.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's trade with all the three destinations increased
steeply during the past few years, according to informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia, Algeria and Mali have considerable untapped mining,
agricultural and other resources which, if exploited sustainably,
can bring improved quality of life to their people, the sources
said. 
</P>
