<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa: New Forex Policy Shows Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The relaxation of foreign
exchange control, which came into effect on Tuesday, shows the
South African government's confidence in transforming the economy
into a global competitor, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing South African Chamber of Business on Tuesday,
Manuel said the significance of abolishing foreign exchange
control regime that had been in effect since 1961, could not be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regulation, private citizens are allowed to
invest up to 200,000 Rand (44,444 U.S. Dollars) in offshore
accounts from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Individuals are also, for the first time, free to hold foreign
currency accounts in South African banks.
</P>
<P>
Manuel pointed out that the relaxation of foreign exchange
control was only one of a series of institutional reforms which
underpinned the government's economic transformation process.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry would radically improve the national
budget process and would, along with next year's budget, be
presenting a three-year expenditure plan, Manuel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
