<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Negative View of CIS Immigrants in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A significant number of Israelis
have largely negative views of immigrants from the Commonwealth
Independent States (CIS), according to a latest poll conducted by
the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that a third of Israelis were "frightened" by
the immigrants, and that more than 40 percent think that they get
too much help from the government, while 63 percent are against
encouragement of mass immigration from the CIS.
</P>
<P>
Some 700,000 Jews have immigrated to Israel from the former
Soviet republics since the beginning of this decade.
</P>
<P>
The immigrants, most of whom are intellectuals, including
high-tech personnel, engineers, doctors, have made considerable
contributions to the socio-economic development of the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
But the native Israelis claim that the immigrant inflow
has caused high rate of unemployment and crimes.
</P>
<P>
The poll touched off an uproar in the Knesset (Israeli
parliament) Immigration and Absorption Committee (IAC) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Natan Sharansky, chairman of the CIS immigrants party
Yisrael B'aliyah, expressed bitterness at the findings, calling
it "the saddest thing that's happened to me in the 10 years
I've been in Israel."
</P>
<P>
Sharansky, who is also minister of industry and trade, said
that, of all the "unpleasant thing" going on in the country
today, "the saddest and most painful is to see the poll results
which clearly show Israelis reject immigrants."
</P>
<P>
Sharansky noted that he was "shocked" by the poll's findings,
and stressed the important contributions made by the immigrants
to the Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
He complained that immigrants were now being seen as a
"foreign, dangerous, competitive, and threatening minority." He
added that the stigmas concerning immigrants from the CIS today
were more serious (now) than in the past, with the talk of a
"strategic threat," a Russian mafia, and even of a possible
takeover of the country.
</P>
<P>
He charged that the Israeli society now not only ties crime
and prostitution to new immigrants, but also attaches such
stigma to leaders of the Jewish community from the CIS.
</P>
<P>
Naomi Blumenthal, chairwoman of the IAC said that the episode
of Zvi Ben-Ari, who is under investigation allegedly for mafia
crimes, has worsened the standing of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"Every other Russian immigrant is suspected of being a
mafioso. As a result, businessmen from the CIS will think twice
about investing here," she said.
</P>
<P>
Blumenthal added that the survey results showed the failure
of efforts to educate the public about the subject.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli public has not yet internalized the fact that the
state has no raison d'etre without immigration," she warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
