<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Abolishes Fixing of Mid-rate for Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The central bank of Thailand has,
as of today, abolished the practice of fixing daily the official
exchange rate for the Thai currency baht, according to the Thai
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand said in a statement released today the
baht would now be allowed to trade under managed float and that
the mid-rate would no longer be fixed on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
On the last trading day, June 30, the mid-rate to the US dollar
was fixed at 25.79 baht, four satang up from the previous fixing
last Friday. The actual trading is normally at around 26 baht to
the dollar, as against about 25 baht a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the move is aimed at stabilizing the
baht, preventing heavy speculation and easing fears of a
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the central bank admitted that the move would
drive the value of the baht down in the next few days, but the
currency will pick up and stabilize in the long run.
</P>
<P>
The bank will publish from time to time the exchange rates
between the baht and foreign currencies for use as a reference
rate in the conversion of foreign currencies into baht.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that allowing the baht to float will lead to
the depreciation of the currency.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the central bank has resisted pressure to devalue
the baht and economists are divided over if a baht devaluation
would benefit the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
