<HEADLINE> Environment Management Training Programs Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Botswanan President Ketumile
Masire has urged African countries to design sustainable training
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Masire said to achieve this, African states have to adopt a
collaborative approach to pool their needs and chart out a
sustainable wildlife and environmental management.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to the community of the College of African
Wildlife Management Mweka, the only one of its kind in Africa, in
the town of Moshi, northern Tanzania on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The president said African countries have to be aware of the
present highly competitive world and the need for each country to
exploit her resources for the common good.
</P>
<P>
"We in Botswana are highly indebted to come for training our
people and my country will rely on the students graduating at the
college to conserve the environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Botswanan president pointed out that vision and mission
are ingredients to success, adding that where there is no vision,
people will inevitably perish.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, briefing the president, Principal of the college
David Manyanza said the vision of the college is to be a center
of excellence in providing professional and technical training,
research and consultancy services to meet the challenges of
wildlife management and biodiversity conservation.
</P>
<P>
He further said the college's mission is professional and
technical training to meet the needs of African wildlife
organizations for qualified and competent management staff.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Masire, who arrive here on Monday for a
five-day state visit to Tanzania, visited Florissa flower farm
and some coffee estates in Kilimanjaro region. 
</P>
