<HEADLINE> ASEAN Members to Strengthen Energy Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Energy ministers of the seven-nation
Association of Southeast Asia Nations (ASEAN) today agreed to
further strengthen cooperation in energy development and
conservation, and energy policy and planning.
</P>
<P>
The one-day 15th ASEAN Energy Ministers Meeting adopted a
report on energy cooperation among the ASEAN member countries
prepared by senior officials meeting which was held here on June
30 and July 1.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed matters relating to the implementation of
the Medium-Term Program of Action on Energy Cooperation which
covers the period between 1995 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to amend the ASEAN Cooperation on Energy
Agreement to provide for the accession clause for three would-be
ASEAN members -- Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, which now groups Vietnam, Singapore, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Thailand, Brunei and Indonesia, is scheduled to admit
the three countries this month to achieve "ASEAN 10 vision".
</P>
<P>
The three prospective ASEAN countries participated in the
conference as observers. European Union Energy Commissioner
Christos Papoutsis also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the meeting, Philippine President Fidel Ramos
highlighted energy cooperation efforts among the ASEAN, which
began with the creation of the ASEAN Council on Petroleum in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also called on the region to meet remaining challenges,
including the standardization of energy facilities and the greater
involvement of the private sector in energy development.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Energy Ministers Meeting is one of the regular annual
gatherings of the ministers of the ASEAN member countries in
various areas like finance, trade, science and technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
