<HEADLINE> China Gets More Civil Service Personnel Through Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The choosing of civil servants by
an examination system is an important reform in the means of
selecting or promoting government officials and is being more
widely used in China, according to Liu Jialin, the director of the
Ministry of Labor's Enrollment Through Examination Department.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remark at a recent conference in Dalian, the port
city in northeast China's Liaoning provinc. He explained
that China adopted the policy three year ago and most of the
country's provinces, autonomous regions and major cities have
opened their doors wider to people who want to compete for a
position in the country's mammoth government operation.
</P>
<P>
With the growth in the use of the policy, the instances of
corruption that used to occurre during the selection process has
declined, giving the general public a greater sense of
satisfaction, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He said that next year implementation of the policy will extend
to town or township governments, institutions, and the financial
sector. He emphasized that the quality of new finance officials is
crucial to the healthy development of the country's market
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
