<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Airbus Compete in Sale of Aircraft to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.-based Boeing company and
the Europe-based Airbus company have entered a fierce competition
in selling their aircraft to India.
</P>
<P>
Air India's bid to buy three 200-seater aircraft has acquired a
new dimension with Boeing offering B767-200 as a better
alternative to A310 of Airbus which was under active
consideration, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned airlines of Air India has already had eight
A310s of Airbus, manufactured by the European Consortium.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing company has made a strong pitch for the order by
stating that B767-200 has a longer range than A310 while the price
is cheaper and the maintenance cost comparable.
</P>
<P>
Air India has planned to buy three more A310s to its fleet of
eight in view of the savings in cost on account of training and
spares. By using the same type of aircraft, the company would cut
on time and cost involved in training pilots and engineers.
</P>
<P>
The argument was valid since the number of planes being
purchased now is low, the official quoted Airbus representative as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The value of the deal is estimated to be around 250 million
U.S. dollars for the three planes. However, for obvious reasons
neither Airbus nor Boeing is willing to disclose the best price
they can offer. Tougher competition would result in a better offer
for Air India, yet it may take a long time, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
