<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lankan Newspapers Hail HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Newspapers here have hailed the
return of Hong Kong to China, saying July 1, 1997, is of great
significance in world history.
</P>
<P>
Several newspapers here in Sinhalese or English issued
editorials or articles on the ceremony marking the handover of
Hong Kong to China which took place at midnight in Hong Kong on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
In its editorial, Sri Lanka's leading national newspaper the
Daily News today said, "All Sri Lankans irrespective of their
clan, creed or politics will welcome this historic transfer of
Hong Kong to its motherland and wish the people of Hong Kong and
China success in their united march toward a still better future."
</P>
<P>
"Residents of Hong Kong have welcomed the transfer and the
business community has shown no anxiety," it said. "Actually,
prospects for Hong Kong look brighter."
</P>
<P>
"Citizens of Hong Kong together with their compatriots in the
mainland can now look toward a brighter future as China is set on
a path that would make it the world's strongest nation in the next
 millennium," the editorial added.
</P>
<P>
The leading Sinhalese-language national newspaper the Dinamina
Tuesday said in its editorial that the handover of Hong Kong to
China is a significant event in world history.
</P>
<P>
It adds that all Sri Lankans heartily welcome the return of
Hong Kong to its motherland China as the return would undoubtedly
bring a better future to both Hong Kong and China.
</P>
<P>
in an article published in Tuesday's Daily News, Chairman of
the Sri Lanka Association for International Understanding S. D.
Bandaranaike said, "Today, China is much stronger, but is still a
developing country. Hong Kong returned to China on July 1. Macao
will follow suit in 1999 and the Taiwan question will surely be
solved and China's reunification will be realized."
</P>
<P>
"By that time a unified stronger China will make an even
greater contribution to mankind," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Another signed article in the same newspaper on Tuesday said
the resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong by
the People's Republic of China will go into history as one other
example of the success of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence.  
</P>
