<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economic Slowdown Bottoms Out: MAS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The current slowdown in
Singapore's economic growth has bottomed out and the country's
gross domestic product (GDP) should grow between five and seven
percent this year, the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) said
in a report.
</P>
<P>
The MAS said in its just released 1996/97 annual report that
economic growth in the third quarter of last year was the lowest
point in a boom-and-bust economic cycle -- a 10-year low of 3.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that viewed in the context of past business
cycles, the current slowdown in economic growth appears to be of
moderate severity. The slowdown of 1996 was "slightly deeper" than
a similar one in 1992, but "far less severe" than the slump in the
mid-1980s, it added.
</P>
<P>
As for the prospects for this year's growth, the MAS said the
favorable outlook for the world's major economies and global
electronics demand suggests a recovery in economic growth in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
One of the positive sign for the Singapore economy was the
increasing shipments and new orders for electronics goods in the
United States, it said. The United States is a key driver of the
Singapore economy, soaking up about a quarter of the Republic's
domestic exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the MAS acknowledged that the electronics industry
remained vulnerable to the downside risk of a persistent glut in
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
Among the other economic sectors, construction growth should be
boosted by a strong pipeline of projects, said the MAS, noting
that last year, the value of contracts awarded amounted to around
13 billion US dollars, compared to the 11-billion-US-dollar level
of 1995.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Singapore's financial services sector is also
likely to see buoyant growth, mainly because of strong expansion
in foreign currency banking activity, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to React to U.S. Decision on Export Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- India is expected to have its
formal response to the U.S. decision to impose export curbs on its
three scientific establishments -- the Bhaba Atomic Research
Center, the Indira Gandhi Center for Atomic Research and Indian
Rare Earths Limited.
</P>
<P>
India's formal response to the U.S. decision is to be made
after the return here of Minister of State for External Affairs
Salim Shervani today from the United States, Foreign Office
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The United States charged in the decision that the three
establishments have been involved in developing weapons of mass
destruction or the missiles used to deliver these weapons. A
spokesperson of the U.S. Embassy here said that henceforward any
export to these three establishments would require a "special
license."
</P>
<P>
Prior to Shervani's visit, Washington had already imposed
similar export restrictions on India's Bharat Electronics Limited
(BEL).
</P>
<P>
America's decision on export curbs is considered here as
double-standard, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They accused Washington of failing to show the similar
consistency with the countries which receive more sensitive items
toward the production of dual-use technology.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the decision is a unilateral violation of the 1984
Indo-U.S. memorandum of understanding on science and technology,
which obliges both governments to consult and inform each other
about proliferation-related activities that companies in either
country might take, they noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
