<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auction Method Being Tried in New South China Wholesale Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Futian Wholesale Market in
Shenzhen City in south China's Guangdong Province has become a new
method to sell farm produce.
</P>
<P>
The market held its first auction on June 28 just after opening
for business in a move that is seen as an important way to move
farm products. Officials from the ministries of agriculture and
internal trade, along with local traders and businessmen from Hong
Kong even attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale market has a floor space of 90,000 sq.m. It was
built at a cost of 300 million yuan and is believed to be the
largest multi-purpose wholesale market in China.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that auctions are a good way to do business
and that commodities here will be packed and weighed according to
international standards. And there will be strict quality control
measures as well to bring the market in line with international
practices.
</P>
<P>
The market is operated by the Shenzhen Farm Produce Co. Ltd
which also runs the city's Buji Farm Produce Wholesale
Market. Most of the vegetables consumed by Shenzhen's three
million people, as well as nine percent of the fruit, and 40
percent of cereals and edible oils are handled by the Buji
Wholesale Market. It sold 1.3 million tons of goods in 1996 and
had 6.88 billion yuan in sales.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugurating ceremony, the city's vice-mayor Zheng
Tongyang vowed to make a contribution to providing local people
with a wide range of farm produce, and pledged to serve Hong Kong
successfully, and to increase production and supply of vegetables
and non-staple foodstuff, increase the variety, and to improve
quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
