<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Amends Laws for More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday amended
three laws designed to give foreigners the right to acquire
property in the country.
</P>
<P>
The amendments were aimed at encouraging foreign investment in
the ailing real estate sector as well as boosting the overall
economy, according to the Bangkok Post today, quoting government
spokesman Varathem Rattanakorn.
</P>
<P>
The three amendments, subject to parliament approval, will
allow those foreigners who marry Thai people to buy one rai of
land (6.25 rai to the hectare), same as overseas investors who
bring more than 25 million baht capital (960,000 U.S. dollars) to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Currently Thai women who marry foreigners lose their property
rights.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendments, however, investors who do not use the
land within two years will forfeit their holdings and it would be
sold by the director-general of the Land Department.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners would also be allowed to buy up to 100 percent of
condominium units in each project in Bangkok with the condition
that the common area of the condominium project which houses
central facilities does not exceed five rai.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners would also be allowed to rent land on a 99-year
lease replacing the existing 30-year contract, according to the
spokesman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Records First Trade Surplus in 30 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea turned in a trade surplus
of 98 million U.S. dollars last month for the first time in the
last 30 months, keeping the trade deficit for the first half of
this year at under 10 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the monthly report of the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry, exports last month increased by
9.2 percent to 12.346 billion dollars while imports were contained
at 12.249 billion dollars, up just 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade surplus on a customs clearance basis
took the total accumulated trade deficit this year to 9.359
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The turnaround in trade from a perennial deficit is the result
of improving performance by leading sectors such as
semiconductors, petrochemicals and iron and steel, ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The effect of the appreciation of the Japanese yen is expected
to begin surfacing in the third quarter of this year, thus making
South Korea's export prospects even brighter, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The international competitiveness of South Korean products has
suffered in the global market with the yen depreciating from 109
Yen to a dollar to 123 in April. More recently in May, the
exchange rate has been around 119 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
