<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- Representatives of highly indebted countries on
the American continent will meet in Honduras on July 2-4.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of government and non-government from Bolivia,
Nicaragua, Guyana and Honduras and delegates of the World Bank and
other development organizations will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Economists estimate that Argentina will produce
10 billion tons of milk by 2000, double 1990 production levels as
100,000 cows have been added to the dairy herd since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Production has been expanded to capture a larger slice of the
Mexican dairy market. Mexico is a major importer of skimmed milk
powder and plans to increase imports of cheese and liquid milk.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The apple and pear harvest in Uruguay is expected
to rise by 3.2 and 1.2 percent respectively this year over last
year.
</P>
<P>
The apple harvest is estimated to reach 66,280 tons and pears
19,825 tons this year.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Carlos Casasus, president of the Mexican
Telecommunications Comission, said that some 30 national and
international companies are interested in the local telephone
service market which is expected to grow dramatically over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico there are 10 telephone lines for every 100
inhabitants, but the number is expected to rise to 60 lines for
every 100 inhabitants within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Starting on July 1, the new one-year partial
extension of the agreements granted by Mexico to Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras to foster trade will become
effective.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 products from the four Central American countries
will have access to the Mexican market at preferential tariff
rates under the new extensions to the agreements.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Experts have revised their forecasts of average
Chilean copper prices this year up marginally on initial
projections. They now estimate average prices will rise to between
1.05 dollars and 1.10 dollars a pound, against a previous forecast
of 1 to 1.05 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The price of copper reached an average of 1.11 dollars per
pound during the first half of this year, an average of 2.88 cents
less than the same period last year. Prices in the first six
months of 1996 fluctuated between 1.02 dollars and 1.23 dollars a
pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
