<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Plans for New Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States today defended
plans by its Energy Department to begin controversial new
underground nuclear weapons-related tests Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman John Dinger told a news briefing
that the experiments would not violate a global test ban.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that subcritical experiments are...
consistent with the provisions of the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that other countries would comply with the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, just as we are," Dinger said.
</P>
<P>
However, 44 congressmen last week urged the Clinton
administration not to go ahead with the experiments, saying that
they violate the spirit of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the U.S. is setting a precedent for other
countries to conduct similar experiments.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Department plans two experiments this year and four
more next year. The first, code-named "Rebound," will take place
in Nevada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
