<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports Up During January-April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The value of Thai exports in the
first four months of the year grew to 478 billion baht (18.38
billion U.S. dollars), 3.52 percent higher than the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to ASEAN members expanded the most, by 11.75 percent,
to a total of 106 billion baht (4.08 billion dollars), according
to Business Economics Department figures, available today.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States yielded 81.7 billion baht (3.14
billion dollars), up 7.58 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This was due to a recovery in the U.S. economy and the
relaxation of some trade barriers, particularly on endangered
turtles, allowing more exports of Thai frozen shrimp, fish and
squid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai exports to the European Union and Japan fell in
the first four months, with the European market down 2.1 percent
to 73.5 billion baht (2.83 billion dollars) and Japan down 1.35
percent to 76.8 billion baht (2.95 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the 18 export categories that had been sluggish in recent
months, 10 had seen increase in the first four months, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 items, exports of thread and synthetic fiber rose
by 15.85 percent, canned fish rose by 14.66 percent, and cars and
parts rose by 289 percent, compared with the same four months of
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong SAR Government, Thailand Sign Visa-free Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), Tung Chee Hwa, and
Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn signed a vise-free
agreement here this morning.
</P>
<P>
This is the first agreement signed since Tung was sworn in as
the HKSAR chief executive in the small hours of July 1.
</P>
<P>
The document, in effect as of today, is on mutual exemption of
visa requirement for holders of HKSAR passports to visit Thailand
and Thai passport holders to visit Hong Kong for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Tung said at the signing ceremony: "The signing of the
agreement reflects the Thai government's confidence in the 'one
country, two systems' concept and Hong Kong's continued stability
and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive added that he had no doubt that other
countries would follow suit in joining the increasing list of
countries or regions granting HKSAR passport holders visa-free
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab Chaiyasarn said that Thailand firmly believes that
this Agreement will pave the way towards even greater cooperation
in all aspects of relationship between the Kingdom of Thailand and
the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
So far, 25 countries and regions have announced granting
visa-free access to HKSAR passport holders, 10 countries and
regions have agreed to grant visa-free access to SAR passport
holders, while five countries have announced that SAR passport
holders will be accorded the same treatment as BN(O) passport
holders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Confident of "One Country, Two Systems" Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
said today he is confident of the success of the "one country, two
systems" concept in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason to doubt it," Prodi told a grand reception
held by the Chinese Ambassador to Rome, Wu Minglian, attended by
nearly 1000 people.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Hong Kong's return is the most important event of
the last few years and he is confident that the "one country, two
systems" concept will succeed in Hong Kong because it is in the
interests of China and all its friendly countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said his country's relations with China and
its Hong Kong Administrative Region will further develop.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Nicola Mancino said the return of Hong Kong is
a historically natural event. He hoped that Hong Kong would remain
stable after its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The President of the Chamber of Deputies (lower house), Luciano
Violante, congratulated China on Hong Kong's return. "This is
indeed an important day for China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Amintore Fanfanni, 90, also attended
tonight's reception. He praised the solution of the Hong Kong
issue and said that China will grow stronger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
