<HEADLINE> Holyfield Might Fight Tyson Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Evander Holyfield said Tuesday
that a third fight with Mike Tyson, who had bitten him on both
ears, was possible once Tyson has proved he has mended his biting
way.
</P>
<P>
"I would never say I would never fight him," Holyfield said in
Atalanta of a third fight with Tyson, who chomping their World
Boxing Association championship rematch to a bizarre end in Las
Vegas last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, he hasn't proven he can control his attitude,"
Holyfield told CNN. "Time will tell. If time permits, and two
years down the road Mike has proven he can control himself, and
he's fighting... I would never say never."
</P>
<P>
Tyson's career was on hold on Tuesday after the Nevada State
Athletic Commission temporarily suspended him and frozen his 30
million-dollar purse pending further disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
Tyson, who also charged across the ring at Holyfield after he
was disqualified, made an abject apology on Monday. He said he
wouldn't appeal any punishment, but pleaded for a chance to redeem
himself.
</P>
<P>
The commission was expected to impose a fine of up to 3 million
dollars and ban Tyson for some time.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield, 34, said he hoped to fight again in November, but
did not mention an opponent.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield said he was heartened by Tyson's apology, which some
cynics saw as a mere bid to lessen his punishment.
</P>
<P>
"He made a big step," Holyfield said. "Any time someone can
admit they were wrong there's a chance they can change." 
</P>
</TEXT>
