<DOCNO> XIE19970702.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian President Praises Hong Kong's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper said today that Hong Kong's return to China marked
the end of the era of colonialism and gave sustenance to his
country's anti-drug trafficking war.
</P>
<P>
The Opium War in China 150 years ago reminded him of the war
against drug-trafficking that his country is facing today, Samper
told the press on his return from the Hong Kong handover
ceremony. He attended the ceremony as president of the
non-aligned movement.
</P>
<P>
Samper said that the drug problem in China at that time was
caused by forced drug consumption and was solved only when China
refused to accept opium deliveries and restricted drug consumption.
</P>
<P>
In a similar way, the drug trafficking problem in the world
today can be solved only when industrialized countries impose
restrictions on drug consumption in their countries, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
