<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mainland, Hong Kong Tourism Gets A Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to China will
provide a good opportunity for mutual growth of tourism
industries, today's China Daily quoted a senior tourism official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony to welcome the first group of Hong Kong
tourists in Beijing after the territory's return, Cheng Wendong,
vice-director of China National Tourism Administration, said the
handover will enhance "Visit China '97" -- the country's current
campaign to attract overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
"We will work together with our counterparts in Hong Kong to
promote the development of our country's tourism industry," the
national English newspaper quoted Cheng as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 Hong Kong tourists, taking an Air China flight,
arrived yesterday in Beijing, where almost every street and major
building were decorated with banners and posters celebrating Hong
Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
The tourists planned to attend several celebrations in Beijing,
according to a tourism official.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, the local tourism department yesterday welcomed
the first Hong Hong tourist group to enter the province by sea
after the return.
</P>
<P>
Also yesterday morning, Hong Kong Dragon Airlines' first flight
to Beijing after the return of Hong Kong arrived in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Carrying about 200 passengers, the aircraft bore a "B", which
represents China's international aircraft, replacing Hong Kong's
"VR."
</P>
<P>
The passengers -- including airline representatives, Hong Kong
officials and tourists -- were warmly received by officials from
the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
</P>
<P>
According to Stanley HC Hui, CEO of Hong Kong Dragon Airlines
Ltd., all of the company's airplanes will carry the "B" within two
or three months.
</P>
<P>
Other Hong Kong airlines will also change their aircraft
signals within the year, CAAC officials were quoted as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
