<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three German Players Storm into Wimbledon Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany took three of the eight
final spots as Boris Becker, Michael Stich and their young
compatriot Nicolas Kiefer produced a spectacular stride into the
quarter-finals of the Wimbledon Tennis Championships here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Kiefer, a former junior Wimbledon finalist,
created the most dramatic upset by snatching a stunning 6-2 7-5
2-6 6-1 win over world number three Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Making his Wimbledon depute, Kiefer beat Alexander Volkov and
the 13 seed Andrei Medvedev of Ukraine on his way to the fourth
round, but his latest performance was easily the best result of
his senior career and also ensured the most Germans in the last
eight at a grand slam in the Open era.
</P>
<P>
In Tuesday's clashes with third seed Kafelnikov, the German
young player jumped at his experienced opponent from the beginning
with powerful smashes and won the first two sets 6:2 7:5. But
Kafelnikov, also 1996 French Open Champion, made a successful
comeback by winning the third set 6:2.
</P>
<P>
After several rain-breaks, the refreshed German youngster staged
more fierce attacks and finally snatched the crutial fourth set
6:2.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Becker's straight sets victory over 9th seed Marcelo
Rios of Chile and and Stich's earlier four-set victory over
Australian doubles expert Mark Woodforde once again demonstrated
that the two former Wimbledon champions also have a good chance of
pocketing another Wimbledon trophy.
</P>
<P>
Todd Woodbridge, who ousted world number two Michael Chang in
the second round meanwhile, earned his first appearance in a grand
slam singles quarter-final by defeating compatriot Pat Rafter 6-7
6-4 7-6 6-3. Britain's Greg Rusedski and France's Cedric Pioline
also sailed into the quarterfinal clashes by beating their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
World number one Pete Sampras and defending champion Richard
Krajicek remained locked in a battle with 12th seed Patrick Rafer
of Chile and British number one Tim Henmen as their matches were
suspended because of dusk.
</P>
<P>
In the women's events, world number one Martina Hings, third
seed Jana Novota of Czech Republic, fourth seed Iva Majoli of
Croatia and Spanish tennis veteran Sanchez Vicario booked their
places in the women's singles quarterfinal battleground. Russian
promising young girl Anna Kournikova also cruised into the
quarterfinal after beating Czech player Helena Sukova. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
